<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B3AFFF7FF18B8AB96ACAAE9" box="[136,237,1468,1489]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Lectotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3AFFF7FE1AB8AB941EAAEA" author="Leuenberger, B. E." box="[394,607,1468,1490]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref17611" refString="Leuenberger, B. E. (1986) Pereskia (Cactaceae). Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 41: 1 - 141." type="journal article" year="1986">Leuenberger 1986: 59</bibRefCitation>
):— 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3AFFF7FD13B8AB9561AAE9" author="Dillenius, J. J." box="[643,800,1468,1490]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" refId="ref16631" refString="Dillenius, J. J. (1732) Hortus elthamensis, vol. 2 [Alter]. Sumptibus auctoris, London, 437 pp." type="book" year="1732">Dillenius (1732</bibRefCitation>
: Fig. 294 on Plate 227, image of the 
<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B3AFFF7FB1CB8AB92A5AAEA" box="[1164,1252,1468,1490]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">lectotype</typeStatus>
available at: https:// bibdigital.rjb.csic.es/viewer/11970/?offset=#page=163).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3AFFF7FF18BB3297ECA82F" blockId="43.[136,1452,1573,1995]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3AFFF7FF18BB3296B0A907" bold="true" box="[136,241,1573,1599]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Notes:—</emphasis>
Plumier found 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3AFFF7FE08BB329421A907" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1768" box="[408,608,1573,1599]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pereskia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aculeata">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3AFFF7FE08BB329421A907" box="[408,608,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Pereskia aculeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
growing on Union island and it was reported from Bequia by Ralfe (1893). We failed to find this species anywhere, either growing wild or in cultivation. On Union island we asked local people, one of whom was familiar and very interested in the local flora, and nobody could recognise the species from photographs. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3AFFF7FEB3BB869791A993" author="Howard, R. A." box="[291,464,1680,1707]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref17096" refString="Howard, R. A. (1952) The vegetation of the Grenadines, Windward Islands, British West Indies. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 174: 1 - 129." type="journal article" year="1952">Howard (1952)</bibRefCitation>
reports that Union island was extensively cultivated in the nineteenth century and the vegetation there today is probably all secondary growth that has developed over the last 100 years or so. If 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3AFFF7FADABBA293EAA9F7" box="[1354,1451,1717,1743]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pereskia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3AFFF7FADABBA293EAA9F7" box="[1354,1451,1717,1743]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Pereskia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was native to the island in the seventeenth century in a natural setting, it was probably exterminated when the land was turned over to agriculture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3AFFF7FF2DBA3694C9A890" blockId="43.[136,1452,1573,1995]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3AFFF7FF2DBA369797A803" author="Hughes, G." box="[189,470,1824,1851]" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" refId="ref17166" refString="Hughes, G. (1750) The Natural History of Barbados. Published by the author, London, 314 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 47069" type="book" year="1750">Hughes (1750: 162–163)</bibRefCitation>
describes a species called “Gooseberry Shrub” which he found growing on the “Estate of the Honourable John Maycock, Esq; in St. Lucy’s Parish”. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3AFFF7FCC5BA52925EA867" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1768" box="[853,1055,1861,1887]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Pereskia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="43" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aculeata">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3AFFF7FCC5BA52925EA867" box="[853,1055,1861,1887]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Pereskia aculeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the common name “ 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3AFFF7FAAFBA5293EDA867" box="[1343,1452,1861,1887]" name="Barbados" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Barbados</collectingCountry>
gooseberry” and is probably the species described by Hughes. We did not see this species on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3AFFF7FB09BA7E9342A8BB" box="[1177,1283,1897,1923]" name="Barbados" pageId="43" pageNumber="68">Barbados</collectingCountry>
but it is still in cultivation there (pers. comm. S. Carrington).
</paragraph>
